bug.short_desc: qooxdoo discards the stack trace of DOMException's

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 1220 Screenshot
The class qx.log.Logger discards the stack trace of DOMExceptions.
Our application catches all errors and logs them into a database. By this way, we get many exceptions that occur in the wild. There are cases where customers get DOMExceptions. The problem is that the stack trace of these DOMExceptions are not logged. We get the String "{ 20, 25, 2, 3, 1, 10, 15, 5, 13, 24, 11, 14, 19, 8, 9, 6, 7, 22, 18, 12, 23, }" where we would expect the stack trace. This issue can be reproduced in the qooxdoo playground - see attached Screenshot.PNG and attach PlaygroundCode.txt.
The problem is that the method qx.log.Logger.__detect detects the type of the exception. The method does not have a special case for "instanceof DOMException". Therefore this method detects the type "map". The method qx.log.Logger.__serialize serializes only the first 20 fields of the map. But the class DOMException contains lots of constants like ABORT_ERROR: 20, DATA_CLONE_ERROR: 25. Therefore the class qx.log.Logger only serializes the first 20 constants and then discards the useful data.
We are not able to implement a workaround, because the methods __detect and __serialize are private. We are also not able to implement a hook that is executed before the class qx.log.Logger reformats the exceptions. All exception hooks always get the exception object that is reformated by the class qx.log.Logger.
The result is that we get useless stack traces. Now we know that our customes get exception and are not able to analyze the reason for this problems.
I could think of two different ways to fix this issue: A) Implement a case for "DOMException" in the class qx.log.Logger B) Catch all DOMEXceptions in the class qx.bom.Stylesheet and repack them into a different class

Option A is the way to go, I think. There are many possible causes for DOMExceptions, not just in bom.Stylesheet, so the logger should be able to serialize them. Unfortunately in Gecko, DOMExceptions aren't instances of Error or even DOMException for some reason, so we have to rely on duck typing. Also, only WebKit and Opera attach stack trace information to them.
Fixed with 5c5b829a (master) 276e798c (branch_2_1_x)
